to provide
the money even if the federal
government doesn't

21:44.102 --> 21:45.904 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
pay for it.

21:45.937 --> 21:50.642 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So they get hit to the tune of
maybe $8 million
a month for every 100,000 people
they cover.

21:50.676 --> 21:54.146 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, right now,
President Trump
appears to be dangling this
as...

21:54.179 --> 21:55.981 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROBERT LASZEWSKI: Yes.

21:56.014 --> 21:59.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You could call it
a bargaining
chip in his negotiations over
the budget with

21:59.785 --> 22:00.752 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the Congress.

22:00.786 --> 22:02.154 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROBERT LASZEWSKI: Right.

22:02.187 --> 22:04.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What would happen
if this money
just stops flowing?

22:04.389 --> 22:06.258 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What happens?

22:06.291 --> 22:09.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT LASZEWSKI: The first
thing that happens
is people's benefits continue to
flow to them.

22:09.594 --> 22:14.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The cost-sharing would continue
to at least
the end of the year, because the
insurance

22:14.066 --> 22:16.001 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
company has to provide the
support.

22:16.034 --> 22:18.970 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the money would come out of
the insurance
company's pocket.

22:19.004 --> 22:24.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The insurance company would then
turn around
and increase rates for 2018,
probably about

22:24.209 --> 22:30.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
15 percent just for this, in
addition to probably
15 percent rate increases
typically that Obamacare

22:30.215 --> 22:32.084 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
would get in 2018 anyway.

22:32.117 --> 22:36.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And what happens
to these exchanges
at the national -- the federal
exchange and

22:36.788 --> 22:38.590 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the state exchanges?

22:38.623 --> 22:41.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT LASZEWSKI: Well, health
insurance companies
have generally been losing a lot
of money

22:41.259 --> 22:42.728 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in the health insurance
exchanges.

22:42.761 --> 22:44.363 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This would make things far
worse.

22:44.396 --> 22:49.868 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, you have already got a
teetering, relatively
unstable situation going on now.

22:49.901 --> 22:53.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The fundamental problem with
Obamacare is,
we haven't gotten enough healthy
people to

22:53.972 --> 22:56.408 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
