30:36.868 --> 30:41.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On Friday, the Taliban reminded
the world
that it remains a force to be
reckoned with.

30:41.573 --> 30:46.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Two of the top national security
officials
in the Trump administration have
just visited

30:46.411 --> 30:47.579 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the country.

30:47.612 --> 30:49.380 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
William Brangham reports.

30:49.414 --> 30:53.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The defense
secretary's
surprise visit to Kabul
underscored growing

30:53.451 --> 30:56.287 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
U.S. concerns about Afghanistan.

30:56.321 --> 31:00.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Secretary Mattis made that clear
after meeting
with President Ashraf Ghani and
other leaders.

31:00.191 --> 31:02.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES MATTIS, U.S. Secretary of
Defense: 2017
is going to be another tough
year for the

31:03.027 --> 31:09.334 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
valiant Afghan Security Forces
and the international
troops who have stood and will
continue to

31:09.367 --> 31:13.338 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
stand shoulder to shoulder with
Afghanistan
against terrorism.

31:13.371 --> 31:17.642 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Just three
days before,
Taliban fighters, disguised as
government

31:17.675 --> 31:21.546 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
troops, killed at least 140
Afghan soldiers.

31:21.579 --> 31:25.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Officials believe the final
death toll will
be higher, making this the
single deadliest

31:25.483 --> 31:28.052 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
attack on an Afghan base in
years.

31:28.086 --> 31:30.822 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It happened at a compound in
northern Balkh
province.

31:30.855 --> 31:35.193 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Also today, at
least four
security guards were killed when
a suicide

31:35.226 --> 31:40.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
bomber hit a U.S.-operated base
in the east
of the country, all this amid
reports that

31:40.431 --> 31:45.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Russia is funneling weapons to
the Taliban,
something the top U.S. commander
in Afghanistan

31:45.904 --> 31:46.871 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
essentially confirmed.

31:46.905 --> 31:48.840 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

31:48.873 --> 31:51.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN NICHOLSON, Commander U.S.
Forces, Afghanistan:
We had the overt legitimacy lent
to the Taliban

31:51.943 --> 31:58.116 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by the Russian that really
occurred during
late last year beginning through
this process

31:58.149 --> 31:59.918 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they have been undertaking.

31:59.951 --> 32:03.821 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
QUESTION: So, to be clear, you
are not refuting
that they are sending weapons?

32:03.855 --> 32:04.856 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

32:04.889 --> 32:06.124 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN NICHOLSON: Oh, no, I am not
refuting
that.

32:06.157 --> 32:07.792 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Russia has
denied aiding
the insurgents.

32:07.825 --> 32:12.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it lends urgency to the U.S.
decision
whether to deploy more American
troops in

32:12.063 --> 32:15.967 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a war that's now in its 16th
year.

32:16.000 --> 32:20.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more on the situation in
Afghanistan,
we turn to David Sedney, who was
deputy assistant

32:20.538 --> 32:26.577 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
secretary of defense for
Afghanistan, Pakistan
and Central Asia during the
Obama administration.

32:26.611 --> 32:31.049 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's now acting president of the
American
University of Afghanistan, and
joins us via

32:31.082 --> 32:33.284 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Skype from Kabul.

32:33.318 --> 32:35.219 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
David Sedney, thank you very
much for being
here.

32:35.253 --> 32:38.823 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Can we -- let's talk first about
this attack
on Friday.

32:38.856 --> 32:45.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Afghan forces have already
lost thousands
of soldiers to the Taliban over
the last few

32:45.363 --> 32:46.331 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
years.

32:46.364 --> 32:48.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How significant is Friday's
attack?

32:48.366 --> 32:50.234 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID SEDNEY, Former Defense
Department Official:
I would have to say that this is
a very significant

32:50.268 --> 32:51.970 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
attack.

32:52.003 --> 32:55.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is probably the largest
attack the Taliban
have ever carried out on Afghan
forces.

32:55.940 --> 33:02.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was done with a kind of
sophistication
and planning that I think even
surprised many

33:02.413 --> 33:04.148 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
people here.

33:04.182 --> 33:09.220 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it shows the Taliban have a
reach and
a capability that is something
that people

33:09.253 --> 33:10.989 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
just didn't expect.

33:11.022 --> 33:13.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: As you say,
this attack
shows, I don't know if you want
to call it

33:13.124 --> 33:15.727 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the audacity, but the audacity
of the Taliban.

33:15.760 --> 33:21.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it is also, is it not,
something of an
indictment of the Afghan forces
to have allowed

33:21.165 --> 33:24.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the infiltrators who helped
perpetuate this
attack and to allow themselves
to be caught

33:24.902 --> 33:26.337 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
off-guard like this?

33:26.371 --> 33:29.540 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID SEDNEY: Well, I think
certainly shows
a failure of intelligence.

33:29.574 --> 33:34.979 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It shows that there needs to be
improved leadership
on the Afghan forces.

33:35.013 --> 33:41.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I have to say that the
Afghan forces have
fought bravely and well in
repeated engagements

33:41.052 --> 33:46.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with the Taliban over the last
several years,
after, to be frank, the Obama
administration

33:46.691 --> 33:51.863 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
made a too hasty and poorly
planned withdrawal,
leaving the Afghan forces
without the kind

33:51.896 --> 33:54.465 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of support and the kind of
leadership that
they needed.

33:54.499 --> 33:59.337 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Obviously, we
need as robust
an Afghan fighting force as we
can to counter

33:59.370 --> 34:00.805 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the Taliban.

34:00.838 --> 34:03.541 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do you think this kind of an
attack will hurt
recruitment going forward?

34:03.574 --> 34:05.810 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID SEDNEY: I don't think it
will hurt recruitment.

34:05.843 --> 34:10.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, the experience that I
have seen here
is, after attack, recruitment
tends to go

34:10.481 --> 34:11.449 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
up.

34:11.482 --> 34:12.884 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But the real issue here is not
recruitment.

34:12.917 --> 34:17.155 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
The real issue here is
leadership, leadership
and mentoring.

34:17.188 --> 34:23.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Afghan forces have a real
large number
of very capable junior and
middle-level officers

34:23.327 --> 34:26.898 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that the United States and our
allies have
played a major role in training.

34:26.931 --> 34:31.536 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But the upper levels of
leadership is an area
where we have not given the kind
of sustained

34:31.569 --> 34:35.273 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
attention over the last decade
or so.

34:35.306 --> 34:37.408 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's where the real
problems lie.

34:37.442 --> 34:42.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's why, as you mentioned
earlier,
the minister of defense, the
chief of staff

34:42.513 --> 34:45.016 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
