have been replaced.

34:45.049 --> 34:49.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I would have to say, many
people here
believe it's well past time that
that kind

34:49.187 --> 34:50.988 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of change in leadership
happened.

34:51.022 --> 34:53.925 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: More broadly,
the top U.S.
commander there, General John
Nicholson, said

34:53.958 --> 34:57.929 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that the security situation in
Afghanistan
is at a stalemate.

34:57.962 --> 35:00.631 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I wonder, do you agree with
that assessment?

35:00.665 --> 35:02.567 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID SEDNEY: Yes, I do.

35:02.600 --> 35:08.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have a situation where the
Afghan security
forces are able to prevail in
direct engagements

35:08.272 --> 35:14.745 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with the Taliban, but because of
continuing
support from Pakistan, because
of the Taliban's

35:14.779 --> 35:20.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ability to strike anywhere
anytime, and because
of weakness in enablers,
particularly air

35:20.251 --> 35:24.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and intelligence, the Afghans
forces haven't
been able to gain an advantage
on the battleground.

35:24.956 --> 35:28.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: We mentioned
also at the
returning that the Russians have
been supporting

35:28.626 --> 35:30.495 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the Taliban increasingly.

35:30.528 --> 35:33.297 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Can you help us understand, why
do the Russians
want to support them?

35:33.331 --> 35:39.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID SEDNEY: The Russians see
Afghanistan
as an area, I believe, where
they can try

35:39.604 --> 35:43.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and take advantage of the United
States, try
and drive a wedge between us and
some of our

35:43.708 --> 35:51.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
allies, and also an area where
they have the
ability to strengthen their
long-term strategic

35:51.282 --> 35:53.084 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
position.

35:53.117 --> 35:55.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Lastly,
General Nicholson
also said, in order to break
this stalemate,

35:55.753 --> 35:59.590 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
billions of dollars and
thousands more U.S.
troops might be needed.

35:59.624 --> 36:01.425 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Do you think that will do it?

36:01.459 --> 36:05.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If that is granted, if the money
comes, if
the troops come, will that fix
this?

36:05.863 --> 36:12.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID SEDNEY: I think that those
are important
components, but there are two
other equally

36:12.837 --> 36:14.805 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or I would actually say more
important components.

36:14.839 --> 36:21.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The first is improved Afghan
leadership, both
at the ministry level and at the
corps level

36:21.779 --> 36:23.514 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the military.

36:23.548 --> 36:28.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There really needs to be a
replacement of
many of older generals that
should have been

36:28.119 --> 36:33.157 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
retired many years ago, and
younger leaders
need to be moved up.

36:33.191 --> 36:37.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But finally and most importantly
is the role
of Pakistan.

36:37.328 --> 36:42.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Pakistan's support for the
Taliban is what
makes them as capable as they
are, the ability

36:42.466 --> 36:51.709 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to have arms, armed men,
explosives sent across
the border, with no restrictions
at all from

36:51.742 --> 36:55.913 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Pakistan, that's what's enabled
the Taliban
to continue to fight the way
they have.

36:55.947 --> 37:00.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And until that safe haven in
Pakistan is addressed
one way or another, this
conflict is going

37:00.184 --> 37:01.919 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to continue.

37:01.953 --> 37:03.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
David Sedney,
acting president of the American
University

37:03.988 --> 37:06.591 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of Afghanistan, thank you very
much.

37:06.624 --> 37:14.332 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DAVID SEDNEY: Thank you,
William.

