in my machine
shop, when we get somebody new,
we don't expect

39:39.944 --> 39:42.012 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
them to be able to do everything
on the first
day.

39:42.046 --> 39:46.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that there are a lot
of Trump
voters out there I have heard
from who say,

39:46.550 --> 39:48.619 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
you know, give him a chance.

39:48.652 --> 39:53.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a very steep learning
curve when it
comes to running the United
States.

39:53.090 --> 39:55.426 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Amy, it is
like everything
else.

39:55.459 --> 39:57.128 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So much of this is in the eye of
the beholder.

39:57.161 --> 39:58.362 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
AMY WALTER: Well, that's exactly
right.

39:58.396 --> 40:00.331 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think the learning curve
thing is very
important.

40:00.364 --> 40:06.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Remember, this is the first
president we have
elected in our time who has
never held political

40:06.470 --> 40:10.307 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
office and who's never had
military office.

40:10.341 --> 40:11.308 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

40:11.342 --> 40:13.010 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is a big learning curve.

40:13.043 --> 40:14.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the people around him has a
learning curve
and Congress has a learning
curve.

40:14.945 --> 40:19.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Most of the Republicans in
Congress have never
worked with a Republican
president before.

40:19.216 --> 40:23.487 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, structurally, though, that's
first this
president I think has time to
sort of right

40:23.521 --> 40:25.289 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the ship.

40:25.322 --> 40:28.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The first 100 days to me not as
important
as the next 100 or 200 or 400 as
we get closer

40:28.959 --> 40:30.728 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to the midterm elections.

40:30.761 --> 40:35.065 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Structurally, his advantage is
that this as
a president who has all levers
of power in

40:35.099 --> 40:36.066 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Washington.

40:36.100 --> 40:37.067 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They have the House.

40:37.101 --> 40:38.869 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They have the Senate.

40:38.903 --> 40:41.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, while I agree that there is
a learning
curve and people are going to
cut them some

40:41.405 --> 40:46.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
slack, saying you're few, get
some notches,
take some time before you can
put some notches

40:46.710 --> 40:51.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on your belt, at some point, if
you have all
the levers of power and you're
still not able

40:51.315 --> 40:53.818 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to get anything done, I think
that's going
to be a problem.

40:53.851 --> 40:57.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Part of what you
have been
both have referring to, Tam, is
he's raised

40:57.488 --> 40:59.256 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
expectations himself.

40:59.290 --> 41:04.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I have been hearing analysts
in the last
few days, and reading them,
saying he needs

41:04.462 --> 41:06.997 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to lower expectations.

41:07.031 --> 41:12.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we do have a sense, don't
we, coming out
of these first three months of
what kind of

41:12.570 --> 41:14.538 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
presidency this is going to be?

41:14.572 --> 41:15.539 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Don't we?

41:15.573 --> 41:17.274 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Haven't we learned something
from this?

41:17.308 --> 41:21.779 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: We have certainly
learned how
President Trump operates.

41:21.812 --> 41:27.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He operates on sort of an ad hoc
basis, that
the White House, that Oval
Office is very

41:27.518 --> 41:33.657 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
open, that he brings people in,
that he is
very available, that he does --
for all of

41:33.691 --> 41:38.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
his talk of the lying media and
the fake news,
he does a huge number of
interviews, where

41:38.362 --> 41:42.099 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
he's more available than past
presidents.

41:42.132 --> 41:47.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what we don't know is if
that is how he
will govern for the rest of his
term.

41:47.204 --> 41:51.108 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He talks about being a very
flexible person.

41:51.141 --> 41:54.912 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we with simply don't know if
that flexibility
means that he will change again.

41:54.945 --> 42:00.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, like President Clinton
started off
with a very rough first 100
days.

42:00.417 --> 42:03.354 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
People widely described it as
disastrous.

42:03.387 --> 42:09.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ultimately, he changed chiefs of
staff and
changed the way he ran his White
House, and

42:09.260 --> 42:15.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
then, having lost the Congress,
cooperated
with Republicans in Congress and
got some

42:15.466 --> 42:16.967 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
things done.

42:17.001 --> 42:19.336 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Amy,
presidents do learn
from their mistakes, don't they?

42:19.370 --> 42:20.971 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
AMY WALTER: That's the goal.

42:21.005 --> 42:21.972 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

42:22.006 --> 42:23.574 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
AMY WALTER: Right.

42:23.607 --> 42:27.645 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And to Tamara's point about
President Clinton,
he did -- that was a rough 1993.

42:27.678 --> 42:30.981 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in 1994, it's not just that
he had a bad
midterm election.

42:31.015 --> 42:35.286 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
His party lost control of the
House, for the
first time in 40 years.

42:35.319 --> 42:40.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, to me, what I'm looking
at in terms
of the number is not just where
he is, President

42:40.891 --> 42:43.694 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Trump is in comparison to where
other presidents
were in their first 100 days.

42:43.727 --> 42:47.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when I look at the number
where he is
now, at 40 or 42 percent, and
look at where

42:47.698 --> 42:53.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
other presidents were close to
their midterm
elections who were at 40 percent
or 42 percent,

42:53.304 --> 42:55.406 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they lost lots of seats in
Congress.

42:55.439 --> 42:57.875 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In many cases, they low control
of Congress.

42:57.908 --> 43:01.478 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So it is imperative for him to
start getting
some wins.

43:01.512 --> 43:04.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Structurally, he has the ability
to do it,
but now he has got to start
delivering.

43:04.381 --> 43:06.483 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And he has got to
make up some
ground.

43:06.517 --> 43:07.718 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
AMY WALTER: Right.

43:07.751 --> 43:11.255 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Tam, we did note
that you're
in Chicago.

43:11.288 --> 43:16.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Obama was there today
to make his
first sort of public
presentation since leaving

43:16.994 --> 43:17.962 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
office.

43:17.995 --> 43:19.930 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, what did you see?

43:19.964 --> 43:24.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: Well, what I saw
is a post-president
who is trying his best to not
talk about his

43:24.902 --> 43:26.604 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
successor.

43:26.637 --> 43:31.775 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was on stage with six young
people who
are active in -- sort of
civically active.

43:31.809 --> 43:36.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he said that he believes
that a big part
of his post-presidency will be
to try to figure

43:36.313 --> 43:42.720 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
out how to get the next
generation involved
in public life and giving back
and in politics.

43:42.753 --> 43:48.025 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He talked about concerns about
people simply
not voting or becoming cynical.

43:48.058 --> 43:50.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But what he didn't talk about
was President
Trump.

43:51.028 --> 43:54.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, for those people who were
hoping that
President Obama would come back
into public

43:54.865 --> 44:00.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
life and join the resistance,
that doesn't
appear to be how he plans to
spend his post-presidency.

44:00.638 --> 44:02.072 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Sounds like he is
holding off.

44:02.106 --> 44:03.841 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
AMY WALTER: Yes.

44:03.874 --> 44:07.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, there's a great irony, of
course, in
President Obama as a face of the
resistance.

44:07.177 --> 44:12.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We talked throughout the Obama
era about the
so-called Obama coalition
voters.

44:12.316 --> 44:13.951 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
But guess what?

44:13.984 --> 44:17.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Those voters, who included a lot
of young
people, only turned out for one
Democrat,

44:17.421 --> 44:18.822 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and that was Barack Obama.

44:18.856 --> 44:20.658 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They didn't turn out in midterm
elections.

44:20.691 --> 44:25.663 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They didn't turn in the way that
Democrats
had hoped for Hillary Clinton.

44:25.696 --> 44:28.399 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Will they then turn out for
another Democrat
is the big question.

44:28.432 --> 44:32.302 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A lot of
Democrats are holding
their breath, crossing their
fingers, or whatever

44:32.336 --> 44:33.904 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
people do when they're hoping.

44:33.937 --> 44:36.306 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Amy Walter, Tamara Keith, thank
you both.

44:36.340 --> 44:38.142 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
See you next Monday.

44:38.175 --> 44:42.780 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: You're welcome.

44:42.813 --> 44:47.451 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
AMY WALTER: You're welcome.

44:47.484 --> 44:53.824 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally tonight,
a conversation
with Sheryl Sandberg about
coping with grief

44:53.857 --> 44:56.593 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and resilience in the face of
adversity.

44:56.627 --> 45:01.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's the subject of a new book
in which
she writes candidly about a
personal tragedy,

45:01.465 --> 45:04.268 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the loss of her husband, Dave
Goldberg.

45:04.301 --> 45:08.605 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I visited her at Facebook's
headquarters in
Menlo Park, California.

45:08.639 --> 45:13.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our interview took place nearly
two years
after Sandberg and her husband
went on vacation

45:13.677 --> 45:16.180 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in Mexico with friends.

45:16.213 --> 45:21.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Sandberg woke up from a poolside
nap, saw
that Dave wasn't there, and soon
went looking

45:21.618 --> 45:23.721 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
for him.

45:23.754 --> 45:28.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She found him lying on the floor
of the hotel
gym next to the treadmill.

45:28.425 --> 45:32.129 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As they later learned, he had
suffered a cardiac
arrhythmia.

45:32.162 --> 45:35.099 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He was just 47 years old.

45:35.132 --> 45:40.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As the chief operating officer
of Facebook,
and one of the best known female
executives

45:40.537 --> 45:46.310 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the business world, Sandberg
had all the
resources and support one could
imagine.

45:46.343 --> 45:51.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But none of that would lessen
the grief that
engulfed her and their two young
children.

45:51.381 --> 45:54.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHERYL SANDBERG, COO, Facebook:
In those early
days and weeks, it feels like
you're not going

45:54.952 --> 46:01.291 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to get through a minute, let
alone a day.

46:01.325 --> 46:05.796 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My biggest fear was that my kids
would never
be happy again, that their
happiness would

46:05.829 --> 46:09.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have been wiped away in that
same instant
we lost Dave.

46:09.466 --> 46:12.770 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are people who had been
through loss
and been through real adversity
who told me

46:12.803 --> 46:13.771 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
it gets better.

46:13.804 --> 46:15.706 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I didn't believe them.

46:15.739 --> 46:21.111 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Ten days later,
when she returned
to work, it was hard to focus on
running a

46:21.145 --> 46:28.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
social media giant, with 17,000
employees
and more than a billion daily
users.

46:28.352 --> 46:33.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Suddenly, one of the most
successful women
in business was struggling to
hold it together

46:33.490 --> 46:35.325 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
at the office.

46:35.359 --> 46:41.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHERYL SANDBERG: When Dave first
died, I felt
like I was in a void, like I
couldn't breathe,

46:41.064 --> 46:42.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or catch my breath.

46:42.566 --> 46:46.336 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I thought at first -- I just
thought, I'm
never going to get through this.

46:46.370 --> 46:47.437 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I can't contribute.

46:47.471 --> 46:49.139 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I can't even get through a
meeting without
crying.

46:49.173 --> 46:54.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A month after his
death, she
posted a tribute to Dave on
Facebook.

46:54.044 --> 46:59.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She wrote about mistakes she had
made in the
past when friends lost loved
ones.

46:59.716 --> 47:05.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She included advice from a close
friend about
how to handle a father-son
event.

47:05.522 --> 47:08.292 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Option A, Dave, wasn't
available.

47:08.325 --> 47:14.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Instead, the friend said it was
time to grab
onto option B. But he used
stronger language

47:14.364 --> 47:15.632 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
than that.

47:15.666 --> 47:19.036 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It became Sandberg's mantra, and
it's the
name of her new book.

47:19.069 --> 47:22.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHERYL SANDBERG: There are
things you can
do, steps you can take to help
yourself and

47:22.873 --> 47:25.375 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
your kids recover.

47:25.409 --> 47:29.479 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I learned that resilience,
it's not something
we have one set amount of.

47:29.513 --> 47:32.850 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a muscle, and we build it.

47:32.883 --> 47:38.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if this helps anyone, even
just a little
bit, themselves or a friend,
then I think

47:38.555 --> 47:39.990 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I will have found some meaning
in this.

47:40.023 --> 47:43.393 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Is the book also
about helping
you get through it?

47:43.427 --> 47:47.464 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHERYL SANDBERG: The book is
trying to help
other people hear what I
couldn't hear at

47:47.497 --> 47:48.465 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the beginning.

47:48.498 --> 47:50.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It does get better.

47:50.434 --> 47:51.535 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I will always miss Dave.

47:51.568 --> 47:53.403 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I miss Dave every day.

47:53.437 --> 47:57.875 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But that feeling of not being
able to breathe
has passed.

47:57.908 --> 47:59.610 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I can breathe now.

47:59.643 --> 48:04.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, sometimes, I think of him
and cry, but,
sometimes, I think of him and
smile.

48:04.281 --> 48:07.651 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And my children can think of
their father
and smile.

48:07.684 --> 48:11.355 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I want other people going
through this
to know it's possible.

48:11.388 --> 48:17.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: "Option B" is not
just about
Sandberg's personal journey and
loss.

48:17.194 --> 48:21.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It offers ideas and advice for
people who've
experienced their own trauma.

48:21.899 --> 48:27.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Co-written with psychologist and
bestselling
author Adam Grant, the book puts
a big emphasis

48:27.771 --> 48:30.641 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on what Sandberg calls the
elephant in the
room.

48:30.674 --> 48:35.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHERYL SANDBERG: It's not just
the loss, or
the cancer, or losing a job, or
someone in

48:35.445 --> 48:37.281 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
your family going to jail.

48:37.314 --> 48:39.182 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's the silence that surrounds
that.

48:39.216 --> 48:46.056 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, when I lost Dave, I had
this overwhelming
grief, but also just this
isolation I had

48:46.089 --> 48:47.858 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
never felt in my life.

48:47.891 --> 48:52.930 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I had always felt really
connected to my friends,
neighbors and family, people I
work with.

48:52.963 --> 48:55.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But when I came back to work,
people barely
spoke to me.

48:55.799 --> 48:58.602 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They looked at me like I was a
deer in the
headlights.

48:58.635 --> 49:00.070 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I know they meant well.

49:00.103 --> 49:03.073 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They were afraid to say the
wrong thing, so
they said nothing at all.

49:03.106 --> 49:07.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What's just one
of the ways
that people should be able to
take away from

49:07.077 --> 49:11.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
your experience about how to
reach out to
someone who's going through
something like

49:11.848 --> 49:16.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this, something traumatic like
this, and for
those who are going through it
themselves,

49:16.186 --> 49:20.557 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who aren't accustomed maybe to
reaching out,
or who aren't comfortable, for
whatever reason?

49:20.590 --> 49:25.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHERYL SANDBERG: If you're
trying to help
someone who's facing adversity,
the first

49:25.896 --> 49:30.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and most important thing is to
acknowledge
the pain.

49:30.200 --> 49:34.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Before, if I had a colleague or
a friend who
had lost someone, who was going
through cancer

49:34.871 --> 49:37.574 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
treatment, I thought bringing it
up to them
was reminding them.

49:37.607 --> 49:39.943 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, I was silent.

49:39.977 --> 49:41.678 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Losing Dave taught me how absurd
that was.

49:41.712 --> 49:43.647 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You can't remind me I lost my
husband.

49:43.680 --> 49:46.483 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I know that every minute of
every day.

49:46.516 --> 49:52.122 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And so, when people said
nothing, particularly
in the beginning, how are you
felt like, how

49:52.155 --> 49:53.623 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
are -- how am I?

49:53.657 --> 49:55.525 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I just lost my husband.

49:55.559 --> 49:56.927 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And they were asking.

49:56.960 --> 49:59.796 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I took that as the standard
American I'm supposed
to -- greeting.

49:59.830 --> 50:01.098 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm supposed to say fine and
move on.

50:01.131 --> 50:02.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But they meant it.

50:02.966 --> 50:08.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when I learned to say, I'm
not great,
or I'm really sad today, or
thanks for asking,

50:08.872 --> 50:13.043 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't want to talk about it
right now, I
was letting them acknowledge.

50:13.076 --> 50:15.479 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so it's really on both sides
to acknowledge.

50:15.512 --> 50:20.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Sandberg also
writes about
how important it is not to blame
yourself.

50:20.550 --> 50:26.123 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SHERYL SANDBERG: When Dave first
died, I thought
it was my fault.

50:26.156 --> 50:30.060 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The initial report said he'd
died of head
trauma from falling off an
exercise machine.

50:30.093 --> 50:33.096 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My brother's a neurosurgeon, and
he told me
that wasn't true.

50:33.130 --> 50:37.234 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When we got the autopsy, we
realized he had
died of a cardiac arrhythmia.

50:37.267 --> 50:43.306 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I still blamed myself, and I
blamed myself
for a long time.

50:43.340 --> 50:47.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when Adam told me that,
because I was
blaming myself, I was going to
keep my kids

50:47.878 --> 50:54.251 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from recovering, because I was
going to keep
myself from recovering, that
really helped.

50:54.284 --> 50:57.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have to show ourselves
compassion, the
same compassion we would show a
friend.

50:57.888 --> 51:03.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Sandberg said
that, ultimately,
family, friends and co-workers,
including

51:03.460 --> 51:07.297 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
her boss, Mark Zuckerberg, made
a huge difference.

51:07.330 --> 51:12.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Not everybody may go back to a
supportive
environment, making it even
harder for them.

51:12.769 --> 51:18.208 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what do you say to people
who are thinking,
how am I going to face
co-workers, what if

51:18.241 --> 51:22.813 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
my employer doesn't give me the
time or the
space or the understanding that
I need?

51:22.846 --> 51:29.086 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHERYL SANDBERG: Yes, we have so
much to do
to make it easier for people at
work.

51:29.119 --> 51:30.087 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm really lucky.

51:30.120 --> 51:31.488 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Facebook has great policies.

51:31.521 --> 51:35.025 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We offer a lot of bereavement
leave, a lot
of leave of all kinds.

51:35.058 --> 51:37.694 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we have done even more since
Dave died
for people.

51:37.727 --> 51:43.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we need our workplaces and
then our public
policy to give people the paid,
paid time

51:43.266 --> 51:46.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
off they need, because, for a
lot of people,
if the time is unpaid, they
can't take it.

51:46.970 --> 51:52.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Sandberg has
become increasingly
outspoken about the workplace,
family life

51:52.109 --> 51:53.777 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and women's equality.

51:53.810 --> 51:59.749 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Her 2012 book, "Lean In," served
as a call
to many women to become more
assertive.

51:59.783 --> 52:05.355 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, to some, Sandberg's tone
smacked of wealthy
white privilege.

52:05.388 --> 52:11.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She was criticized in some
quarters for failing
to appreciate what single
parents and non-traditional

52:11.862 --> 52:13.730 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
families go through.

52:13.763 --> 52:18.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now she's expanded the message
to stress the
role of government and society
in the lives

52:18.768 --> 52:20.504 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of women.

52:20.537 --> 52:23.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHERYL SANDBERG: We are the only
developed
country in the world, the only
one, without

52:23.573 --> 52:25.709 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
paid maternity leave.

52:25.742 --> 52:28.645 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we need that, and paid
paternity leave,
so men and women are equal.

52:28.678 --> 52:32.649 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're one of the only developed
countries
without paid family leave.

52:32.682 --> 52:37.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think a lot about going
through everything
I went through, and also
worrying about paying

52:37.287 --> 52:43.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a basic health care bill, about
single mothers
who wake up every day in this
country and

52:43.326 --> 52:47.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
worry about whether they can
take care of
a sick child, or lose their job
that they

52:47.898 --> 52:50.834 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
need, about the minimum wage we
have.

52:50.867 --> 52:54.371 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Two-thirds of minimum wage
workers are women.

52:54.404 --> 52:56.940 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Minimum wage hasn't been raised
at the federal
level in forever.

52:56.973 --> 52:58.441 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's unacceptable.

52:58.475 --> 53:03.547 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Unexpectedly, joy
is also an
essential message in the book.

53:03.580 --> 53:06.850 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's something Sandberg feared
she would never
feel again.

53:06.883 --> 53:10.220 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SHERYL SANDBERG: I thought it
would always
feel that way.

53:10.253 --> 53:14.925 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the sadness is still here,
but it doesn't
feel like I'm trapped in a void
anymore.

53:14.958 --> 53:19.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I have joy, and I have
laughter, and I
have moments with my kids where
we remember

53:19.462 --> 53:24.434 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
their daddy with real joy, and
we look at
pictures and videos.

53:24.467 --> 53:29.039 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I want anyone going through
hardship to
know that it does get better.

53:29.072 --> 53:31.541 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We all have things we can
appreciate.

53:31.575 --> 53:34.811 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We all have moments that we can
notice the
joy.

53:34.844 --> 53:37.647 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We all can find gratitude for
being alive.

53:37.681 --> 53:42.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that doesn't mean that every
story has
a happy ending, because it
doesn't.

53:42.085 --> 53:49.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there are things we can do
to build resilience
in ourselves and each other that
make us stronger.

53:50.026 --> 53:55.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Sheryl Sandberg
has not only
written this book, "Option B,"
about her experience.

53:55.999 --> 54:00.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She's encouraging people going
through tragedy
to form support groups to be
there for each

54:00.937 --> 54:02.339 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
other.

54:02.372 --> 54:03.974 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's the "NewsHour" for
tonight.

54:04.007 --> 54:05.141 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm Judy Woodruff.

54:05.175 --> 54:07.310 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Join us online and again right
here tomorrow
evening.

54:07.344 --> 54:16.086 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For all of us at the "PBS
